<subSubSection id="92C10CD08F971D24552A36966684F0F1" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="08028C7ADD7AE82ABADF0203CAA744D8" pageNumber="2">
The 
<taxonomicName id="49265B04A8D43B9C5806F8B4209916CD" pageNumber="2" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sarcoglanidinae">Sarcoglanidinae</taxonomicName>
(family Trichomycteridae) constitutes one of the most intriguing South American catfish assemblages. This group is known from a few specimens, which are classified at present into six genera and seven species (Costa, 1994; de Pinna, 1998; de Pinna &amp; Winemiller, 2000). The scarcity of available specimens may be due to their very small size (usually less than 25 mm SL as adult), and their apparent preference for difficult to sample sandy banks of rivers and streams (Costa and Bockmann, 1994; Costa, 1994). Most sarcoglanidines are considered miniaturized fishes (Weitzman and Vari, 1988; Costa and Le Bail, 1999) and all except for one species are poorly pigmented, with translucent body in life. Two taxa, 
<taxonomicName id="3448187720677308C0CF6B38B6D4CFAF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0D725466-0021-48FD-B2D9-9370280B62B5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Sarcoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sarcoglanis simplex Myers &amp; Weitzman 1966:279" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplex">Sarcoglanis simplex Myers &amp; Weitzman</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="35C62D5C25E0C317A7C010C710FF9F57" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F3DA639-4603-4566-832D-58DA00E78D27" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Malacoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Malacoglanis gelatinosus Myers &amp; Weitzman 1966:282" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gelatinosus">Malacoglanis gelatinosus Myers &amp; Weitzman</taxonomicName>
possess an uncommon deep body, hypertrophied saclike adipose organ above pectoral fin, and absence of premaxillary teeth (Myers and Weitzman, 1966), and three taxa, 
<taxonomicName id="2D6E5B643B3839F50192963605A3D5ED" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0D725466-0021-48FD-B2D9-9370280B62B5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Sarcoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sarcoglanis simplex Myers &amp; Weitzman 1966:279" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplex">S. simplex</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2E5809E6C202E4CA264B0F3FF85A70C8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F3DA639-4603-4566-832D-58DA00E78D27" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Malacoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Malacoglanis gelatinosus Myers &amp; Weitzman 1966:282" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gelatinosus">M. gelatinosus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="2E76EB2EF1B38746A4858718356DE7E8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3E32A3E6-17D3-4940-BAAE-8F31B6333387" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Stauroglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Stauroglanis gouldingi de Pinna 1989:7" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gouldingi">Stauroglanis gouldingi de Pinna</taxonomicName>
, have few or no opercular and interopercular odontodes (Myers and Weitzman, 1966; de Pinna, 1989; Costa, 1994). The three pairs of barbels found in other trichomycterids (maxillary, rictal and nasal barbels) are also present in sarcoglanidines, although nasal barbels are often shortened. In addition, some sarcoglanidine taxa have a pair of a barbel-like structures on the ventral surface of the head (Myers and Weitzman, 1966; Costa and Bockmann, 1994). All species of five genera, 
<taxonomicName id="FAD8D7A629D79245BBF02D64B3E788FE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:2BD2AE4E-D095-461D-9725-EFDABCECE8DF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Sarcoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sarcoglanis Myers &amp; Weitzman 1966:279" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Myers">Sarcoglanis Myers &amp; Weitzman</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="05A6FBC885454686B403DC78C31AED13" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:845FFA6E-3B93-43C5-BCA5-944D6C3F42EE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Malacoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Malacoglanis Myers &amp; Weitzman 1966:281" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Myers">Malacoglanis Myers &amp; Weitzman</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E2C9B5F3D339307283E1F5EE68A055B4" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:75591A55-B270-434D-92F6-58BADA5C9021" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Stauroglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Stauroglanis de Pinna 1989:6" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Stauroglanis de Pinna</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8852C1045B6E69F98075D29173C4FEBF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:72CFE91C-32FA-4E5F-911D-83DF216F82E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Stenolicmus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Stenolicmus de Pinna &amp; Starnes 1990:77" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Stenolicmus de Pinna &amp; Starnes</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A78588D012284F8805BE429D8B6BB1BC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:51EEBE8B-E1EC-4CAB-A48D-73F543DA1F0A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Ammoglanis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ammoglanis Costa 1994:208" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ammoglanis Costa</taxonomicName>
are endemic to the Amazon. In contrast, the other taxon, 
<taxonomicName id="B3A9C56B212C950C5054DB52BB6727CF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8366B788-7803-4524-849A-0CE04316EF26" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Microcambeva" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microcambeva barbata Costa &amp; Bockmann 1994:718" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="barbata">Microcambeva barbata Costa &amp; Bockmann</taxonomicName>
, is endemic to a small coastal basin of southeastern Brazil, the Rio 
<normalizedToken id="6B82BA45EAB8E80CFC1E0ED746430739" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="FA7EB61AEB628BD7DD3A4B7CC0858974" originalValue="João">Joao</normalizedToken>
drainage, in the Brazilian Atlantic forest area (Costa &amp; Bockmann, 1994). The present paper reports the description of a new species of 
<taxonomicName id="06A0B0B91FF79CC7281D9F40BA5F16DB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A32C7369-033F-469F-98D5-39BECA080AA2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Microcambeva" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microcambeva Costa &amp; Bockmann 1994:718" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microcambeva</taxonomicName>
, the largest sarcoglanidine fish, known from the rio Ribeira do Iguape basin, southeastern Brazil, which is about 500 km, in a straight line, from the type locality of 
<taxonomicName id="4011239AD444E7931DE69CBC7CD764EA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8366B788-7803-4524-849A-0CE04316EF26" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trichomycteridae" genus="Microcambeva" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Microcambeva barbata Costa &amp; Bockmann 1994:718" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="barbata">M. barbata</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
